Yes, using the '==' operator and the 'equals()' method can yield different results when comparing Strings in Java, so it's a good practice to use the 'equals()' method for String comparisons.

The '==' operator in Java is a reference comparison. That is, it checks whether the two references point to the exact same object in memory. This means it becomes true only if both Strings are exactly the same — they must occupy the same memory location.

The '.equals()' method, on the other hand, checks the actual value or content of the strings, that is, it checks if they have the same sequence of characters. Two strings can be different objects in memory but still be equal in terms of their characters. This is why using '.equals()' is a more accurate method for comparing Strings.

Therefore, in general, you should use '.equals()' for String comparisons:

```java
String a = new String("Hello");
String b = new String("Hello");
System.out.println(a == b); // Returns false because they are different objects
System.out.println(a.equals(b)); // Returns true because their content is the same
```

The '==' operator may be appropriate in a few specific scenarios, like comparing primitive types (like int, char, boolean, etc.) or Strings that have the same compile-time constant literal. These comparisons make sense at compile-time, so there's no runtime check required:

```java
public static void main(String[] args) {
    int x = 5;
    int y = 5;
    System.out.println(x == y); // true - both x and y are of same integer type

    String literalString = "String literal!";
    String anotherLiteralString = "String literal!";
    System.out.println(literalString == anotherLiteralString); // true - both are compile-time constants
}
```

